segments.text: Okay, the captain of the team.
And we're talking about, what are we talking about now, the captain?
Yeah, he was the captain of that company.
Oh, okay, the captain of that company.
And the president of the class.
I'm not going to call their names.
And the president of the class now had those people come back here wearing a badge.
we like Frank.
This is twenty years later see.
They changed a lot in twenty years.
They mature a little bit.
Now we'll take a little, just on the board paddling I'll do that.
Well let's wait because we're going to, was that another one of the problems when you were commandant?
What did you try to do when you were commandant?
Well, yes, yes.
Now, for...
I, as chairman of the, the commandant is chairman of the discipline committee.
I didn't want, I didn't give that discipline committee a chance to fire anybody.
The law would fire somebody if he,
If he was tasing, they didn't allow that.
Legislature didn't allow that.
Right.
But I had to, in order to get them to give that up, I had to get pretty tough.
One old boy, I remember he was a junior.
He threw his own captain into the fish tank out here at the class picnic, and he was the meanest man in school with a paddle.
Well, I told those people, you don't have to take abuse.
You don't have to tell me who you are.
But if you've got something that you want me to know, you can just drop me a line and tell me about it.
This old boy was a junior now.
He was real tough.
I went to his place and I said, I want to see you in your trunk.
He got his paddle out.
It had so many notches on it.
I said, you have done, you just got through throwing your own captain into the fish tank.
You're a mean, big, tough guy that somebody's going to straighten you out.
And I'm the guy to do it.
You people are roughed up and mean tough but I'm tougher than any of you.
You're going to move out of your outfit and you're going to live in Devil's Island.
There was an old piece of a dormitory down yonder that the married professors used to live in but then when they abandoned that thing they just left it down there.
It still had lights in it.
I guess it had a few old beds or something.
Now I said, boy, you're going to move out to Devil's Island.
Now you can either do that or you're going to be shipped from A&M College because you've been mean as a son of a bitch.
Now, what you want to do?
You want to go move to Devil's Island or you want to leave school?
Well, he went to Devil's Island.
I didn't hurt him.
That didn't embarrass his parents.
I told you the same thing I did to these boys that carried these things out.
I told you about the no toilet paper on the train.
We went up to Fort Worth.
That was the first court trip.
I told you about that.
I did.
Well, I won't go into that anymore.
I thought I didn't know for sure.
Why did you resign in 1937 as Commandant?
Well, they threatened to strike and of course the board of directors had to begin to take a hand.
And why did they threaten to strike?
Because you were clamping down?
Oh yes, because I didn't live up to my promise.
I told them if they would give up the paddle I would enforce their rams.
And then after a year I thought something over.
I said now here's a ram that I'm making this poor damn freshman carry food.
when he gets caught when he's not guilty at all.
And I don't like to do that.
And so I got out an order that I would not enforce their round for that one thing.
Well they wouldn't take it that way.
You just didn't say that.
You said you would enforce our rounds if we'd give up the paddle.
I was the only one that ever felt that way about it.
As far as I know, the board of directors, the president, and everybody else just figured that I ought to, evidently ought to have done, ought to have enforced those ramps and said nothing about it.
But I'm just not that way.
How can anybody be that way?
You gotta be reasonable.
And so that was it.
The board of directors came up here to make an investigation.
They talked to every senior that wanted to talk to them.
They never did ask to see me.
I went down there and I said, you haven't asked to see me, but now I'm asking to see you.
And I went over this stuff with them.
And they still couldn't figure that I should have done it.
I said, well, now listen, if you don't want my program, you don't want me.
I'm resigning.
They said, oh no.
No, no, no.
We're not going to let you resign.
You'll save us $15,000 on broken furniture and stuff like that.
You made them pay for it.
But that's the only thing they complimented me for.
They could understand those dollars and the fact that I made those boys quit doing that stuff and things like that.
Well, one old boy at the school just kicked all the slaps out of the window, out of the door.
His name was John Crow.
No, it wasn't John, it was his younger brother.

Well, I just told him, I said, now Dr. Walton, I'm not going to stand for that stuff, but will you promise me, Dr. Walton, that you will spend everything I sent, that I saved this school this year, this coming year, will you give them better furniture?
He said, I sure will.
Now that's the only thing that board of directors complimented me on was saving them that money.
And so I just resigned.
And as I said, they wouldn't take my resignation.
He says, we're going to come up here and straighten things out.
Well, that sounded all right to me.
That's all I wanted them to do.
But you know what those darn people did?
No, what?
They double crossed me.
They double-crossed me.
Dr. Walton called me in the middle of the summer, or it might have been late in August.
It had been here, it's been three months now since all this confrontation took place.
Everybody that knew anything about A&M, that they didn't like at least, after all these thousands of freshmen that had run off, I had letters and telegrams from people like that.
backing me up.
The law of the state backed me up.
So, by golly, they couldn't take my resignation because they're backing up people that were doing all these things that are not even legal.
And here I'm trying to straighten it out and they have taken the side of senior class.
And so I just quit.
Then they said, no, we're not going to let you quit.
You've done too much good and decided that $15,000 had saved them.
They couldn't afford to do it because if they took the side of these other people, they'd be on the spot because they're defending stuff that the state of Texas didn't want them to defend.
That senior class got together with me before they struck over at the old line and pleaded with me, please don't change our school.
We'd rather have 1,500 good eggs than 15,000 tea suppers.
I said, don't change our school.
Please don't change our school.
I said, it's not your school.
You've taken it over and you think that you've run it.
you're only allowed to come here.
This is not your school.
This school belongs to the University of the State of Texas, the people of the State of Texas, and I'm not going to let you keep doing what you're doing."
All right.
Then's when this struck.
That had been followed by the incident of the Beale over here, you see.
They just got together to talk things over with me that I had made them a promise.
I finally had to walk out on them.
I said, there's no use in you talking to me anymore, cause you, we're just miles and miles apart.
And I just walked out.
Well then that's when they decided they couldn't take any more of me.
And I had decided that they didn't, it was me or nothing.
And I'd already told the board of directors that.
But they weren't men enough to take my resignation.
They couldn't stand against all this backing that I had all over the state.
They just wanted to ease me out.
And after about three months, Dr. Walton called me in and said, now, Colonel Frank, you've got a lot of friends around here.
A lot of people respect you pretty heavily, pretty deeply.
But the board of directors feels it would be better
just would be better for you to go on back down to the athletic field."
I said, alright.
Alright, Dr. Walton.
I just love you, Dr. Walton, and you're an awful good friend of mine, but
you just, he was getting ready to go to Europe for some, you know, their own business.
And I said, you just have a good time now over in Europe.
So everything's gonna be all right over here.
And I just, I just boiling inside.
I went to Dean Bolton and I said, Dean Bolton, I'm not through fighting.
I don't like to be treated like that.
I'm going to Houston right now and I'm going to run the chairman of the board of directors of this state if I can."
He said, oh, Mr. Anderson, Mr. Anderson, please don't do that.
He said, you set this school back ten years.
Oh, Lordy Dean Bolton, I don't want to do that.
But I said, Dean Bolton, you've got more sense than I have.
I'll do what you said.
He said, well, Mr. Anderson, he said, I'm on your side a whole lot, Mr. Anderson, but I think that you'd be better to do what they said.
He said, Mr. Anderson, you believe in revolution, not evolution.
That's what that good old dean told me.
I guess he's right.
Oh, Lord have mercy.
Well.
So you resigned in 1937.
I go back down to the athletic field.
We win six out of the seven of the first, my next year's.
And then the former students under Coach Bryant got us in trouble.
And I told him, I said, now I'm going to resign, I mean retire in a couple of years, Coach.
I can't take my team to the Texas relays.
I can't take my team to the Drake or the Kansas relays.
I can't take them to the NCAA meet because we're on probation.
And they put track on probation along with football and everything else.
They shouldn't have done it.
They ought to just punish the people that did this thing and your former students did it.
Why?
Tell me about this.
I said, I have nothing to work for, coach.
I haven't had a place to take my teams to.
Please get a youngster and let me work with him for the next two years.
He wouldn't give a darn about track.
He was kind to me.
I'm an old boy that's getting ready to retire.
And who's this now?
Who's this now?
I was getting ready to retire.
No, I know, but who were you talking to?
Brown.
Oh, okay.
Bear Bryant.
Okay.
He didn't care about track either.
Oh, well he had no, he wanted to play football in the spring.
He wanted to play football all year round.
He didn't care about any other sport but track.
But football.
And so, and I said,
Now you do that because if you don't track's going to suffer because I'm leaving here after two years.
I cannot afford to leave now because of my teacher's retirement and social security.
I've got to get those up and I won't be old enough to retire.
But there's things are why there's nothing to work for much.
So he said, oh, coach, you're just doing fine.
He said, we don't need it.
He said, we don't need anything any better.
You're just doing real fine.
And so I couldn't get him to get anybody at all.
Well, two years came around, and now I'm quitting.
And I went to him, and I said, now, coach, I'm going now.
And you haven't got anybody.
nearly July and all the people had been recruited for next year.
Why don't you just get Putnam?
Putnam was a professor who used to come down and help me with the distance man.
He was an old mile champion.
About an old, I saw him run Lincoln, Nebraska.
Win the mile.
And he was down here, and I knew him, and I got him to come out there and help me a little bit.
And he helped O'Ryland and on up to Charlie Thomas for a few years before he stopped.
Well, then he just volunteered this statement when he hadn't got anybody.
He says, Coach, they ought not to be a track coach.
He says, as far as I'm concerned, they ought not to be a baseball coach.
Two professors ought to come down here and run those on a part-time basis.
Now that's what Barry Brown told me.
Wow.
That's incredible, isn't it?
Yeah.
And that explained why he didn't get anybody for those two years.
And of course, Charlie Thomas followed Putnam and Putnam, he just didn't have any time to coach the team.
No.
He is a full-time professor.
Here I am
You know, I was a coach that had all the waiter jobs.
I said we didn't have any help from the former students.
You said that the former students got you in trouble in the 1950s.
Will you tell me about that?
How'd they get you in trouble?
How'd they get you on probation?
By, by, well, all the coaches in the conference teamed up on Barbara Brown.
he was winning.
And I just felt he had just raised the ante, you see.
Because they were doing things about getting people in.
But he gets people in that they couldn't get in, you see.
And he's beaten them.
And they didn't like that.
I think he must have just given somebody or got, I don't think he did it, but I think some former students that had some money did it.
And they teamed up on him and they finally got him.
He left.
Yeah.
But how did you get on probation?
But he got Putnam and Putnam was no time at all.
couldn't do anything with that track team.
He had them one year, and then they got Charlie Thomas.
And it took Charlie some while to build up the team.
And I helped Charlie Thomas.
I helped him.
I worked with those people for four or five or six years, just like I was coaching.
He and Ted Nelson were both runners.
And my strong point
was in the field.
My jumpers and falters and weight men and my hurdlers were better than my runners.
I don't care whether they were short or long runners.
But we did have a mile relay team that wasn't defeated for four years.
I want to show you their picture.
But I was a field man mostly.
And then the people who run the Olympic Games were kind enough to
make me an Olympic coach, and give me field events to coach.
And I had a chance to work with some boys.
Al Orter stills were on the discus.
He threw it for me the first time he was ever in the Olympics.
And he used the swing that I had for him.
Rayford Johnson was the Catholic man.
He used the swing that I gave him.
And he won the decathlon second that year and then the next four years he won the darn thing.
I had boys to win first and second in three events and first in two of them.
On that team it went to Australia.
That was an honor to get up to be an Olympic coach.
And we were the only coaches that's ever done any coaching because that happened to be in the southern hemisphere.
We have Olympics up here in August, late August.
And down there they have them in late November.
So we got that team together in September and coached them.
actually worked with them.
I had a chance to change somebody's form and teach them a better way.
They can't do that now when you're a coach and then you get on the boat.
The day you qualify, you get on the boat and here you go.
And all they can do, coaches, all they can do is try to keep the men from going to sleep.
One poor guy let his sprinter sleep while they were out there running the race.
I have a question about your attempts to control hazing.
Tell me about the hazing problem.
Well, they hazed in a number of ways.
A freshman was more or less, that's a little female red bird.
If the male comes out there and you see the red one, you call my attention to it and I'll go out and feed him.
He won't fly off.
If she's out there to hear me, I'd call him in.
Cardinal, now that's his daughter.
He was out there yesterday feeding her.
He'd take up a grain, he'd run across and she'd open her mouth and he'd put it in her mouth.
Now that's a young one, a young cardinal, female.
Alright now, is this thing still working?
Sure is.
That's okay.
Where am I?
You're talking about the number of different ways in which the Corps hazed.
Yeah.
Well, I've told you about drilling them at midnight.
Yeah.
I would like to give... Now, I'm now back in athletics.
A year or two later, I go down to Corpus.
A year or two later than what?
I go to Corpus with my track team.
During the... What year?
Easter...
period off.
Well, this would be 46, 47, 48, 58, 59, 60, 61, 62, 63, those years.
Down there was my team.
Gibb is up here now struggling in what I'm doing, what I did.
He took up the torch that I passed to him
He's a University of Texas graduate who is now president of A&M College.
He's trying to carry out what I started.
He's trying to break up this business of running everybody off from A&M and keeping them here and graduating them and getting more people to come that are afraid to come.
And he was an important character.
He was a fine man but he had
He didn't know how to make a lot of friends.
He didn't make a lot of friends at A&M College.
But to me, he is the best man that ever put a foot on this campus.
Because he put my baby over.
The legislature backed him.
But now, before it came down to a crisis and they had to back him.
I was down at Corpus now with my track team.
He was in bad with the school because he was trying to carry out the program that I had started.
Seniors, all the seniors went to different places to make a speech during that time, Easter break in school, to get Jeb Gilchrist out.
The senior from Corpus Christi
the son of the mother of the A&M Mother of the Year, fine people.
He got up there and he rang all those people at that A&M club meeting in Corpus.
Old Colonel Bill Sterling, a fine old, he's general now, just a fine character.
a well-known one, he was there, the chairman of that meeting.
Well, that man talked.
Well, I was sitting there with old Cleo Buck, who was the captain of my team in 28.
This is now a long time later.
But he is an alumnus that lives in Corpus.
Bill sees me out back there and he says, Colonel Anderson's here.
I want to come up here and say a word.
come on up here, Frank, come on up here now, don't, don't, don't, back row, other way, come on.
And he said, now, this, you tell us what, what you think about all this stuff that this man's talked about.
Well, I said, Bill, I just, I just 100% disagree with you.
I just back, give Gilchrist to the limit.
He's doing and has done what I couldn't try, I tried very hard to do.
And, uh,
He said, well, he said, well, just sit down here.
He said, freshman, I want to ask you some questions.
What do you think of A&M?
Oh, I think it's fine.
I think it's fine.
He said, school's nearly out now.
He says, I paid the price.
I'll get it even next year.
You'll get it even next year?
What you mean?
Well, I can give them the same treatment they gave me.
And, well, what do you do?
Well, they're not as bad as the paddlers as they said they used to be, but I guess not the worst thing as far as I'm concerned is having to take a cold bath about three o'clock in the morning.
He said,
But he says, it's all right, it's fine, I'm forever a bit of it, because when you're understood anyhow.
Then Bill said, well listen, if they get you up to do that at 3 o'clock in the morning, when in the world do you sleep?
He said, I always sleep in class.
He's just saying what he shouldn't have said, don't you think?
But that, I thought I'd bust right open when he said that.
And Bill said, oh, shucks.
Meeting adjourned.
Meeting adjourned.
So that senior didn't get anywhere down there.
He didn't seem to get anywhere, too many places, because the legislature came out with laws and give gilches intended to enforce them.
And when the,
The captains went over and tendered their resignations.
He said, I hate to see you boys do this to yourself, but all right, I'll accept them.
They didn't say you'd do that.
This is 1947?
Huh?
This is 1947 and the revolt?
Yes.
That would have been in 47.
It could have been in the spring of 48.
Spring of 47.
Well, I guess it could have been the spring of 47.
But I'm down at Corpus now and I wasn't the track coach until 46 and we didn't go down until that year.
It could have been, I think it must have been at least 48.
Okay, 48 then.
And so the captains tendered their resignation.
The captains tendered
The Corps captains tendered their resignations.
Yeah, all the captains, every single captain presented their resignations.
He just kind of hate to have to do it, but you're no longer the captain.
If you want to quit, I'll take your resignation.
Because we don't want you with what you want.
We won't take you for what you want.
We're just going to have to do about some of these things."
And the law was back on us.
And it happened.
A&M started just blooming.
And I started waiting.
I picked up
Because more students were coming.
And I learned my lesson about recruiting.
The first one I got, couldn't make my team.
The third year in school, he couldn't even make my team.
And he was the high school champion quarter miler, but he couldn't make my team.
Why not?
Because they had boys better than he was that didn't go to the state meet and win the darn thing.
But they worked here hard enough to where they could.
Let me show you that relay team.
I can show you.
You want to turn that off now, sir, while?
Sure.
Yeah, I'd like to ask you a couple more questions.
Why were you appointed the first dean of men?
That is a combination job.
The commandant before my time was not the dean of men.
I was the first dean of men, but I was still the commandant.
Why did they decide to have a position of dean of men?
All the big schools had them.
They thought they might as well join.
I used to go to the dean of men's meeting.
Of course, I wasn't in the job very long, but one year it was in Austin, and I attended the dean of men's meeting.
So I did the work of discipline plus the job of dean of men.
It was just a kind of a job.
And then I had a stenographer, a lady, and then two helpers.
And now they have spread out all over.
Between the DNM and the ComNet together, I mean, to have quite a spread of helpers.
Do you remember when Franklin Roosevelt came to Texas A&M in 1937?
I was in charge of that day.
Could you tell me about it?
Well, he came here on his special train.
He got off.
I had to take the responsibility of guarding that man.
We had to submit a route that he would take a parade, and I had to see to it that not another car was parked on that thing.
And then just generally see him in and out.
of the talk he made.
Of course he had to have a little platform to hold up on.
My wife and my two young boys were there.
I think Wally, the younger one, was about five, something like that probably.
The other one was two years older.
Did you get to talk to President Roosevelt?
Did you get to talk with President Roosevelt?
Nothing, just to say hello.
I was not, I just, when I finally came in I just sat down with my wife and two boys.
He stayed there, he had his own guards, but I was in charge and I had to keep, had to keep people
off of that route.
So I had some, I'd call them gray sergeants that worked for me full time, people.
Now they were the people that when these people came back from Fort Worth and had plundered the Texas Hotel, I told you about that,
I got those gray sergeants while these people were drilling on Thursday afternoon and I had written the hotel to the police.

They told me they didn't want us to come there anymore and I wrote them back, just please tell me the names of the people who were in that room where the stuff was gone and we'll do what we can about it.
So while they were drilling on Thursday afternoon, I got my gray sergeants together, and there were four regular army officers that worked for the commandant, not the PMS&T, but the commandant.
That's me.
And we had pass keys to all the rooms, and so we divided up by force, and we gave this man a list of stuff that's in this dormitory and this and this and this,
And while they were drilling, we went there and we got all that stuff.
Didn't I tell you that story?
No.
Well, I don't know if we overlooked that one.
So while they were drilling, we went there, we unlocked their lock, we went in there and we found every bit of that stuff.
One man had run off with a floor lamp.
He was the senior and the...
social secretary.
He had run over the floor lamp.
The balance of them had been satisfied with towels and blotters and a picture of something.
But, oh golly, we got it all.
And so I just sent for those boys one at a time.
And I said, now, they have written to us that they don't want us to come up there anymore.
We can't live with that.
And I don't want to do anything to you that will hurt you deeply.
You think you should have done that, I guess.
It's all right with you to do those things.
And a lot of people do and think nothing about it.
But this hotel writes us that they don't want us anymore.
So I've got to do something to you.

You sit down here, I've got the wrapping paper, and you wrap this thing up, address it back to that hotel, sign this letter that you apologize and promise never to do such a thing like that again anywhere.
We'll go over here and you'll buy the stamps and we'll mail you a package and stamp your letter.
And then, boy,
you're not going to go to any other football games away from home this year.
And they always had court trips in those days.
And that was the first one.
And that's what did it at that hotel.
Next couple of weeks, we went to Houston.
And I wrote to Rice Hotel.
I said, now, I'm working on something up here, and I want your help.
They raided the Texas Hotel in Fort Worth pretty badly two weeks ago, and I popped it to them.
I want you to be sure to get a record of everything that's gone from your hotel.
And let me know.
I got a letter from them a couple of days after the game was over, and they said, oh, don't bother about it.
Don't bother.
One fella took a towel, but please just forget it.
I didn't tell you that story?
That's what I did.
Those things happened.
Now, I talked against the toilet paper incident.
I talked
against the Yale leaders who would exhort these kids, you be there.
If you can't do anything else but catch a freight train, you be there.
If you can't get in a ticket, climb a fence.
You be there.
You've got to support this team.
This school was nuts.
Are you a Texan?
No, I'm from Minnesota.
Huh?
Minnesota, remember I told you I was from Minnesota.
Don't ever ask a man is he from Texas.
I'm a Tennessean, but I've been living out here so darn long and I love it.
I'm a Tennessean and we like Tennessee a lot.
We popularize the north half of Texas.
And a lot of my uncles, I remember an uncle of mine putting his wife and kids into a covering wagon on the head for Texas.
And they're living up here at Wolf City now.
And some of them went further, up to Chillicothe and on out to Quanah.
But up that lane, they're Tennessee people.
Just like my pioneer folks that came across the Alleghenies when nobody owned the land but the Indians.
They did it coming on out here.
Oh, I lose the train of thought.
I get off on so many things.
I was wondering about the relationship.
You were in the physical education department for a while.
And I was wondering about the relationship between physical education department and the athletic department.
I had my privilege of doing what I wanted to do when I went down there.
Coach Norton, I never did like him.
I liked him all right.
He was all right, but he fired all my friends.
And I was coaching under him.
And I wasn't enjoying it.
And when Dr. Walton offered me that job, I took it for two reasons.
I wanted to get away from there and I wanted to crack at this.
Well, I don't know that I had my mind made up about wanting to crack at this, but I must have because I wasn't doing too well in track on account of what was happening up here.
And I felt like maybe I could make a contribution to future track teams, future basketball and baseball teams.

As I said before, they had a hard time maybe getting football players because boys like, as I've told you before now, people are on this, these football players go back and talk about all the way things happened down here.
He kind of stared their nose off and they'd go somewhere else.
Yeah.
I just thought maybe I could help athletics by being the commandant of one.
And I thought I'd give it a quarrel, kind of a challenge to me.
But they didn't want me.
The faculty wanted me.
But the board of directors were all in them.
I only had one man on the board of directors.
He was from San Antonio.
He was on my side.
But they wouldn't let me quit until four months.
And the furor order all passed over.
And now here's another man.
There was an explanation one way or another.
They just had a new man.
A man that I liked.
Colonel Moore was a fine friend of mine, and he picked a commandant that I recommended too.
He picked a commandant, I mean a cadet colonel.
How did you get along with the former students?
Tell me about your relationship with the former students, former student association.
Oh, I had a lot of friends among the former students.
